This article is a press briefing by Press Secretary Jay Carney, Nuclear Regulatory Commission Chairman Greg Jaczko, and Deputy Secretary of Energy Dan Poneman. The briefing addresses the situation in Japan after the earthquake and tsunami, specifically the safety of American citizens in Japan and the impact of the nuclear accident. Chairman Jaczko states that there is a low likelihood of harmful radiation levels in the United States or its territories. Deputy Secretary Poneman emphasizes that the U.S. is providing technical assistance to Japan and stands ready to assist as required. The briefing also includes discussions on the potential impact of the Japan disaster on the global economy, the situation in Bahrain, the possibility of a no-fly zone in Libya, gun control measures, and the status of same-sex marriage legislation in Maryland.